Analysis of a Policing Dataset from Dallas, Texas in 2016

Spoorthi Kalenahalli Basavalingaiah(sk22724)

2023-04-25


Introduction

The purpose of this project is to provide an analysis of a policing dataset from Dallas, Texas in 2016. The dataset used in this project is called 37-00049_UOF-P_2016_prepped, which is available from the Data Science for Good website.


Project Overview

In this project, we will explore and analyze the dataset to gain insights into policing practices in Dallas in 2016. We will focus on the following research questions:

  • What are the demographic characteristics of individuals involved in police incidents?
  • What types of police incidents are most common?
  • Are there any patterns or trends in police incidents based on time, location, or other factors?
  • What is the relationship between police incidents and race/ethnicity, gender, and age?


Data Description

The 37-00049_UOF-P_2016_prepped dataset contains information on police incidents in Dallas, Texas in 2016. The data includes details on the individuals involved in the incidents, the type of incident, the date and time of the incident, and other relevant information.

Time and Date conversion
df$INCIDENT_DATE <- as.Date(df$INCIDENT_DATE, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
df$INCIDENT_DATE <- gsub("00","20",df$INCIDENT_DATE)
df$INCIDENT_DATE <- as.Date(df$INCIDENT_DATE, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
df$INCIDENT_TIME <- format(strptime(df$INCIDENT_TIME, "%I:%M:%S %p"), "%H:%M:%S")
df$INCIDENT_MONTH <- months(as.Date(df$INCIDENT_DATE))
df$INC_MONTH <-format(df$INCIDENT_DATE,"%m")
df$INCIDENT_HOUR <- as.numeric(substr(df$INCIDENT_TIME, 0, 2))
df$INCIDENT_DAY <- wday(df$INCIDENT_DATE, label=TRUE)
df$INC_HOUR <- substr(df$INCIDENT_TIME, 0, 2)
df$INC_DATE <- substr(df$INCIDENT_DATE, 9, 10)

Incidents per month
r1 <- ggplot(df_month, aes(x=INC_MONTH, y =count, group=1)) + geom_line()  + geom_line( linewidth = 1,colour ="steelblue") + labs(x="MONTHS OF 2016", y= "INCIDENT COUNTS", title="1.a Months vs  Incident Rates")  + theme_bw()

The incident rate showed a gradual decline over the course of the year, with the highest rate occurring in March and the lowest rate in December.


Incidents vs time
r2 <- ggplot(df_hour_n, aes(x = INC_HOUR, y = avg, group = "count")) + geom_line( size = 1, colour = "blue") + labs(x="HOURS IN A DAY", y= "INCIDENT COUNTS", title="1.b Hours vs  Incident Rates")+ theme_bw() +

r2

In 2016, the number of reported incidents decreased overall, with peaks observed during the hours of 17:00-20:00 and 02:00, and the lowest number of incidents reported between 04:00-10:00 and at 07:00.


Distribution of crimes across months and days

The analysis shows that the incident counts follow a normal distribution in the months of March, June, July, January, August, and April, while two peaks were observed in December, February, May, and October. A left-skewed distribution was observed in September. On weekdays, the incident rate is normally distributed on Sundays, while Wednesdays exhibit multi-modality with smaller nodes observed on Wednesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, and Saturdays. The average range of incidents for both days and months is between 3 to 20.


Subject race vs Incident Date
# Create a scatter plot with incident dates on the x-axis, subject races on the y-axis, and color-coded points
ggplot(df, aes(x=INCIDENT_DATE, y=SUBJECT_RACE, color=SUBJECT_RACE)) + 
  geom_point(size=2, alpha=0.5) +
  xlab("Incident Date") + ylab("Subject Race")

It is important to note that correlation does not imply causation. Simply observing a relationship between subject race and incident rates does not prove that race is the cause of the incidents. There may be other factors, such as socioeconomic status or location, that are influencing the relationship.

The plot shows that Black people commit more crimes, with peaks in March and May and lower numbers in July and October. The second plot reveals that Hispanics also commit more crimes in March and January, with the lowest incidents in June and October. The third plot indicates that White people have a higher range of incidents in September and a lower range in June. Overall, the graphs suggest that Black and Hispanic individuals commit more crimes in March.

The first plot displays the crimes committed by Black, White, and Hispanic people over all the months, showing a trend that is highest in March for all three groups but significantly higher for Black people. Three peaks are visible for Black individuals in March, May, and September, indicating that they commit more crimes in Dallas. In contrast, the second plot shows that more White officers handled cases committed by Black people, with two peaks in incident handling rates matching those of Black individuals. The number of Hispanic officers handling incidents is slightly higher than that of Black officers, and there is a downward trend for all officer races in December. Overall, there is a sharp contrast between Black individuals and White officers and Black officers and White individuals, and further investigation is needed to confirm whether racism is a factor in Dallas.

Crime Trends by location
# Filter out rows with missing or invalid lat/lon values
df <- df %>% filter(!is.na(LOCATION_LATITUDE), !is.na(LOCATION_LONGITUDE))

# Extract first word of INCIDENT_REASON column
df$reason <- sub("\\s.*", "", df$INCIDENT_REASON)

# Extract unique reasons from REASON_FOR_FORCE column
unique_reasons <- unique(sub("\\s.*", "", df$reason))

# Define color palette for different reasons
color_pal <- setNames(rainbow(length(unique_reasons)), unique_reasons)


# Create map plot
m <- leaflet(df) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircleMarkers(lng = ~LOCATION_LONGITUDE, lat = ~LOCATION_LATITUDE, 
                   color = ~color_pal[sub("\\s.*", "", reason)], 
                   radius = 2, 
                   stroke = FALSE, 
                   fillOpacity = 0.8) %>%
  addLegend(position = "bottomright", 
            title = "Incident Reason", 
            colors = color_pal,
            labels = names(color_pal))

# Show the map
m

Conclusion

Key insights from the data analysis reveal a decreasing trend in incident rates over time, peak incident hours between 17:00 and 20:00, and a contrast in incident rates between Black and White subjects/officers. Additionally, Central Division had the highest number of incidents, and suspects with guns and weapons had recurring peaks in incident rates. Time series analysis provided insights into trends, seasonality, and the racial backgrounds of officers and subjects. These insights can inform effective prevention and intervention strategies.
